The paper presents a robot navigation system that uses symbolic spatial information to navigate in unseen built environments. This involves the use of data structures, sensorimotor perceptions, and a dynamic system to create malleable spatial models for the abstract map. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category, as it deals with the development of a robot navigation system. Additionally, the paper employs artificial intelligence techniques to enable the robot to navigate purposefully, which makes the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category a likely fit. The paper also mentions the use of sensorimotor perceptions, which suggests that the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category may be relevant. Furthermore, the paper deals with the creation of a dynamic system, which suggests that the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category may be relevant. Finally, the paper evaluates the performance of the robot navigation system, which suggests that the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category may be relevant.
